Much stronger. The main turn is now correct: concede bid-stage exclusion, preserve QSL only where its capability is genuinely non-fungible, and sell DSIT on constrained discretion rather than institutional virtue.

I would not treat it as commit-ready yet. Four changes still matter:

- **Fix the statute citation.** Under the Procurement Act 2023, award criteria are **section 23**, not section 26. Section 24 is the relevant section if you discuss refinement of award criteria. Leaving `s.26 award criteria` in the brief is a credibility own-goal. Sources: [section 23/24 notes](https://www.legislation.gov.uk/ukpga/2023/54/notes/division/6/index.htm), [award-criteria guidance](https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/procurement-act-2023-guidance-documents-procure-phase/assessing-competitive-tenders-html).

- **Split “this live call” from “future phases.”** The current ProQure Phase 1 call opened on **27 March 2026** and closes on **29 May 2026**. So “freeze methodology before bid evaluation begins” is already overtaken for this competition unless DSIT formally modifies the procurement documents. The brief should say:
  `For the live 2026 call, the realistic ask is no QSL role in award, but a bounded post-award verification role.`
  `For future calls / Phase 2, freeze and publish methodology before the tender notice.`
  Sources: [ProQure call page](https://iuk-business-connect.org.uk/opportunities/contracts-for-innovation-proqure-scaling-uk-quantum-computing/), [modifying a competitive procurement guidance](https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/procurement-act-2023-guidance-documents-procure-phase/modifying-a-competitive-procurement-html).

- **Narrow the dual-key model.** “Independent body replicates and co-signs” still sounds cleaner than it probably is. If no UK body can really replicate QSL’s full stack, DSIT will hear “ceremonial second opinion.” Make the second key procedural, not mythical:
  protocol approval, witnessed runs, random reruns, deviation log, chain-of-custody sign-off, and authority to require rerun if process drift occurs.
  That is more defensible than pretending there is a peer evaluator of equal depth.

- **Add bright-line prohibitions, not just allowed roles.** DSIT will trust a negative list more than a principles statement. State explicitly that QSL must not:
  advise bidders during the live competition,
  see bidder-confidential materials beyond what is strictly needed to run fixed tests,
  alter benchmarks or thresholds during the competition,
  score, rank, moderate, or join interview panels.

Two non-obvious upgrades would make the brief better:

- **Capability escrow model.** QSL develops the benchmark harnesses, parameter sets, and test scripts, but those artefacts are deposited in a controlled repository so another evaluator can run them if a conflict trigger is hit. That reduces dependence on individual discretion.

- **Red-route model.** Do not treat QSL as institutionally clean or dirty. Route specific vendors out of any QSL-run verification path when there is contemporaneous QATCH co-development on the same subsystem. That gives DSIT a practical off-ramp instead of an all-or-nothing fight.

The strongest final recommendation is probably this: **for the live 2026 competition, keep QSL out of award; for post-award verification and future phases, permit QSL only through pre-published methods, strict prohibited-role rules, and external process assurance.** That is a cleaner, more saleable ask.

